<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-298-480  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 298 480.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  May 4 1989 n1162 p24(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A new tech visitor on the voter's doorstep. (UK political partiesuses computers) (includes related article about kinds of computersbeing used)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cole, Louise.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The UK's political parties are using information technology (IT)with varying levels of success, to get the votes at elections, toadminister the party, to analyze the constituency, and to alimited degree, to provide communications between national andlocal groups.andP;  The Conservative party draws about half of itsvoluntary Conservative Computer Forum from IT professionals, butlocal Conservative groups are only loosely affiliated with thenational party and often do not share software or computer systemsor membership information.andP;  The Labor party has about 1,000members in its Computing for Labor organization.andP;  The SocialDemocratic Party, the Social and Liberal Democrats, and the Greenparty also use computer systems for political marketing, voteranalysis, and administration.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer SystemsApplicationsUtilizationPoliticsPolitical IssuesUnited Kingdom.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>